  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Street child reintegration, foster care and family support</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Projects working with street children often do not fully understand why children end up on the streets. They track how many children take part in activities but do not really know what lasting change happens as a result. This grant will help an international organisation to strengthen its systems for assessing street children&#x2019;s needs and the changes in their lives. The organisation will review and test out a new database in Uganda and Ethiopia and make sure it captures useful and valid information. It will input the data and train staff in how to use it and apply it to individual children&#x2019;s cases, as well as their overall programme. They will share learning with others by producing a training manual, analysing how to make the system available to other projects and carrying out an evaluation of the process. As a result, the organisation will improve its work and influence others who work with street children. Street children in Uganda and Ethiopia will get better quality support from projects and from government because the organisation helping them can assess its impact better. It will also have evidence to lobby governments to train their social workers better and stop simply rounding up children on the street.</narrative>
  </description>
